FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on airplanes (but no cell phone conversations)
Air travelers can hear from departure to landing their electronic devices for reading, working, games, music and use the watching movies, but not on a call with the phone now, the new Directives on Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) were issued in the United States.
However, the passengers should not expect that these changes are implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented, would depend on the airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta told a press conference.
The airlines need the FAA to demonstrate that airplanes meet the new guidelines and that they have updated the training manuals of the flight personnel as well as the arrangements for the storage of the device according to the new regulations.
The FAA stated that it had already received from some airlines plans that want to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Under these airlines were also Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the condition of the plan, we could expand the use of electronic devices very soon approve," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers must turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
It may not start up if the airplane has reached a height of three kilometers and is the captain of the green light.
Upon entering the landing, passengers must switch it off again and may not restart them before the plane landed.
Under the new guidelines could airlines whose planes were protected against electronic interference, allow their passengers to use the equipment even when off, landing and on the runway, the FAA said.
Most new aircraft and other airmen who were converted for the use of Wi-Fi at higher altitudes, should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional association of professional flight attendants, welcomed the changes.
"If the new regime is implemented safely - and we are therefore cooperating closely with the airline -, the two sides will benefit," said Glading.
It is we honestly sorry to feel on this issue as watchdogs.
Never-theless Internet connections for surfing, exchange of emails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometers still prohibited, explained the authority.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices in airplane mode.
So no still "Words With Friends" which Scrabble similar online game, in 2011, played the actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone when he had publicity leave a jet of American Airlines, because he refused to turn off the power while the the aircraft was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops must continue to be stored, since the possibility of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Cell phone conversations during the flight also remain still prohibited.
The regulatory authority for telephone calls is the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
