An advisory committee of industry, which was launched to study this topic by the FAA, recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA has increased to relax restrictions on the use.
Critics such as the Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri argued that there was no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also more difficult to enforce, because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
